{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}
'''ADIME''', or '''Assessment, Diagnosis, Intervention, and Monitoring/Evaluation''', is a process used to ensure high quality nutrition care to patients and clients from nutrition professionals, such as Registered Dietitians (RD) or Registered Dietitian Nutritionist (RDN).<ref name="BauerLiou2011">{{cite book|author1=Kathleen Bauer|author2=Doreen Liou|author3=Carol Sokolik|title=Nutrition Counseling and Education Skill Development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ItNtCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA128|date=21 July 2011|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-133-70807-0|pages=128–}}</ref><ref name="Gresham2016">{{cite book|author=Barbara B Gresham|title=Today's Health Professions: Working Together to Provide Quality Care|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nj5dCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA164|date=8 January 2016|publisher=F.A. Davis|isbn=978-0-8036-5790-8|pages=1–}}</ref> ADIME is used as a means of charting patient progress and to encourage a universal language amongst nutrition professionals.<ref>Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics Evidence Analysis Library. (2007). Nutrition Diagnosis and Intervention: Standardized Language for the Nutrition Care Process. Retrieved July 14, 2014, from http://www.andeal.org/files/File/Nutr%20Diag%20and%20Intervention%20Publication%20Fall%202006.pdf</ref><ref>Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics. (2014). Nutrition Care Process. Retrieved July 14, 2014, from http://www.eatright.org/HealthProfessionals/content.aspx?id=7077</ref>
==Steps== The ADIME process consists of four steps:<ref name="NelmsSucher2015">{{cite book|author1=Marcia Nelms|author2=Kathryn Sucher|title=Nutrition Therapy and Pathophysiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RGlvCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT151|date=1 January 2015|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-44600-7|pages=151–}}</ref><ref name="DeBruynePinna2011">{{cite book|author1=Linda DeBruyne|author2=Kathryn Pinna|author3=Eleanor Whitney|title=Nutrition and Diet Therapy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCduCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT426|date=20 June 2011|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-133-71550-4|pages=426–}}</ref><ref name="MahanRaymond2016">{{cite book|author1=L. Kathleen Mahan|author2=Janice L Raymond|title=Krause's Food & the Nutrition Care Process|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXIwDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA165|date=17 May 2016|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-323-34076-2|pages=165–}}</ref> *Assessment - This step involves collecting data pertinent to the patient, including nutrition-related History, anthropometric Measurements, biochemical data, nutrition-focused physical findings, client history and comparative standards. *Diagnosis - Based on the assessment data collected, a nutrition problem may be diagnosed. Causes and contributing factors are identified. *Intervention - Based on the nutrition diagnosis, problems are addressed that aid in alleviation of the diagnosis’ signs and symptoms. Activities are constructed to enable the patient to work towards objectives set for them by themselves and their nutrition professional. *Monitoring/Evaluation - Progress made on goals and/or expected outcomes is tracked to ensure that nutrition problems are being addressed; adjustments in the Intervention step are made according to progress.<ref name="Boyle2016">{{cite book|author=Marie A. Boyle|title=Community Nutrition in Action: An Entrepreneurial Approach|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyYVDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA181|date=25 March 2016|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-63799-3|pages=181–}}</ref>
